INSERT INTO `Course` VALUES (1,1,NULL,'INTRODUCTION TO MATHEMATICAL MODELLING (VO)','German',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"3.00\"]','[]','[\"Bachelor\"]','[]',NULL,'The course aims to provide students with a foundational understanding of one- and multidimensional analysis. It focuses on the independent application of this knowledge to problems in economics, technology, and natural sciences. Students will also learn to use software tools for modeling and graphing, and develop skills in oral presentation.','- Know the basics of one-dimensional and multidimensional analysis.- Apply this knowledge independently to solve simple problems.- Use suitable software tools for modeling and graphing.- Communicate this knowledge in an oral presentation.',NULL,'- One-dimensional analysis- Multidimensional analysis- Application of analysis to simple problems in economics, technology, and natural sciences- Modeling and graphing using software tools- Solving problems using the learned contents- Communication of knowledge in an oral presentation format','A 90-minute written examination on the lecture contents. Documents and electronic aids are not allowed. At least 50% of the maximum points must be achieved for a positive grade.',NULL,'Mastery of the content from \"MG1 - Mathematical Foundations of Computer Science 1\" and school-level mathematics (fractions, quadratic equations, etc.) is assumed.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"51120\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(2,1,NULL,'School: SPL 5 - Informatik und Wirtschaftsinformatik','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"3.00\", \"12.00\", \"6.00\"]','[]','[\"Bachelor\", \"Master\", \"Master / Bachelor Elective\", \"Master (Version 2022)\", \"Master CS / Master Data Science\", \"Elective\"]','[]',NULL,'This course aims to convey fundamental methods and algorithms for various sub-areas of modeling and optimization. It provides students with the tools to formulate and solve complex problems in various fields. This course aims to have students conduct an IT-oriented project in Computer Science or Media Informatics, building upon previous project experience to tackle more complex tasks and combine advanced knowledge. This course covers foundational distributed Information Systems technologies, including system design, sockets, concurrency, REST, and Service-Oriented Architectures. It involves practical and theoretical work. This course focuses on selected topics in High Performance Computing (HPC), including programming languages, application implementation, performance analysis, and scalability. This course offers an overview of methodologies for the Cloud and Cloud-Edge continuum, applying Patterns and AI techniques for dynamic deployment and reconfiguration in multi-cloud scenarios. The aim is to conduct a substantial IT-oriented project in the field of Computer Science or Media Informatics. This course builds on the experience from Practical Course 1, focusing on higher complexity and the integration of advanced knowledge to solve technical problems. This course provides an understanding of parallelism as a computing primitive. It covers the theoretical foundations of basic problems and state-of-the-art developments in algorithm design for distributed and parallel environments. This course focuses on foundational distributed Information System technologies. It provides interactive discourse and practical project implementation for realistic distributed scenarios. Covers portability and interoperability gaps in Cloud and Edge computing. Explores Patternbased Software Engineering and AI techniques (Semantic and ML) for automated discovery, orchestration, and adaptive deployment. Introduces central methods for organizing and analyzing large scientific data, emphasizing similarity search and data mining on structured data like sets, images, and graphs.','- Understand and apply basic modeling and optimization methods.- Analyze and solve problems using the learned algorithms Demonstrate an advanced understanding of project problems. Apply specialized concepts and methods to achieve suitable solutions. Gain proficiency in carrying out large-scale IT projects independently. Demonstrate an advanced understanding of project-based challenges. Apply specialized methods and techniques to achieve high-level technical solutions. Synthesize knowledge from previous taught modules into a singular large-scale implementation. Recognize which paradigm (distributed vs. parallel) is best suited for new problems. Study the correctness and time complexity of suggested solutions. Conceive, plan, and implement a realistic distributed project. Apply standard best practices and patterns to software architectures. Reason about programs to apply optimisation strategies. Familiarity with program transformations for efficient code. Translate source languages to target languages using assisting tools. Implementation of scalable solutions for large data volumes. Improvement of programming skills for data mining. Teamwork-based solution development. Gain hands-on experience with high-performance computational libraries. Implement and evaluate gradient-based training models.\n\nStudents learn about threat scenarios in distributed systems by understanding component attacks and memory corruption vulnerabilities that lead to network endpoint takeover.',NULL,'Differential equations Linear and nonlinear optimization methods Metaheuristics Random numbers Markov chains Application of the theory to practical problems - Independent processing of project tasks. - Implementation of a prototype. - Writing a comprehensive project report. - Topics available from various research groups. Distributed system design and development with sockets. Concurrency, remote objects, services, and REST. Service-oriented architectures (SOA) and Enterprise Application Integration (EAI). Project implementation and online self-evaluation tasks. HPC programming languages. Application implementation on HPC systems. Performance analysis and scalability. Practical exercises and project work. - Cloud services brokering and cloud orchestrators (Kubernetes, etc.). - Cloud and Cloud-Edge patterns (Architectural, Deployment). - Containers (Docker) and Microservices. - Machine Learning for resource selection on the Cloud-Edge continuum. - Edge Intelligence architectures (Federated Learning). - Advanced independent project processing. - Software/Hardware prototype realization. - Comprehensive project reporting and documentation. - Topics available from groups including: MIS, DM, SWA, Hlavacs (Entertainment Computing), and VDA (Visualization and Data Analysis). Distributed (Graph) Algorithms: LOCAL, CONGEST, CONGESTED Clique models. Problems: Coloring, BFS, APSP, diameter, cycle detection, spanners, spectral sparsification. Parallel Algorithms: Architectures and design principles. Model of computation: PRAM. Problems: Matrix multiplication, minimum spanning tree, shortest paths, connectivity. Distributed system design and architectural paradigms. Development with sockets. Concurrency and remote objects. Services, REST, and Service-Oriented Architectures (SOA). Messaging and Enterprise Application Integration (EAI). Transformation phases. Program representations. Dependence analysis. Code transformations and optimisations. Vectorization and parallelization. - Multi-Cloud and Edge Interoperable scenarios. - Federated Learning and Edge Intelligence. - IoT data learning systems. - Cloud Orchestrators (Ansible, Kubernetes, etc.). - Containers (Docker) and Microservices. - Design tools: Tosca, Terraform, Cloud Formation. - Scientific Data and Feature Spaces. - Distributed data repositories and index structures. - MapReduce and Apache Spark for large data. - Hashing, classification, and clustering. - Analyzing large networks and mining graphs. Computational software: BLAS, LAPACK, PyTorch, PETSc. Neural network models and automatic differentiation. Gradient-based training pipelines. GPU computing with CUDA.\n\n- Binary exploitation. - Feasible network attacks. - Chaining vulnerabilities in lab environments. - Threat scenarios in distributed communication.','Written final examination. At least 50% of the achievable points are required for a passing grade. Evaluation of the entire project, prototype implementation, and written report. Grading scale: 1 (≥87.5%), 2 (≥75.0%), 3 (≥62.5%), 4 (≥50.0%). Part A: Practice-focused exams (76 pts). Part B: Programming tasks (8 pts). Part C: Active participation (16 pts). A passing grade requires >50 total points and >44% in both Part A and B. Grading based on partial assessments (assignments and tests). A positive grade requires at least 30% on each, with an overall score of at least 50% and at most one negative partial assessment. Grade is based on project work. No traditional exam. Grading Scheme: 1 (≥88%), 2 (≥75%), 3 (≥62%), 4 (≥50%). Evaluation of the entire project, the implementation of the prototype, and the written report. Exercises (individual): 20 points. Quizzes (individual): 10 points. Final Oral Exam (mandatory >= 20 pts to pass): 70 points. Grade 1: >= 89 pts; Grade 4 (Pass): >= 50 pts. Part A: Multiple practice-focused exams (76 pts). Part B: Multiple programming tasks (8 pts). Part C: Active participation (16 pts). Grading based on assignments and an exam (equally weighted). Minimum grade of 50% required in both to pass. Project work based (no traditional exam). 1 (Excellent): >= 88%; 4 (Pass): >= 50%. Exercises (presenting solutions in class): 30% Programming assignments (group report + code): 30% Written Midterm: 20% Written Final: 20% Pass requirement: >= 50% combined score of midterm and final exam. Two closed-book written exams and individual projects (Each part must be >= 50%).\n\n- Lab assignments (60%) and final semester exam (40%). Usage of AI tools is strictly prohibited.',NULL,'Good knowledge of single and multivariable differential and integral calculus (within the scope of MG1 and MG2 modules). Mandatory: None. Recommended: Practicum Computer Science 1. Object-oriented programming, UML modelling skills, and Java experience are required. Programming, Software Engineering, basic notions of Cloud Computing. Mandatory: None. Recommended: Completion of Practicum Computer Science 1. Highly recommended: Discrete Mathematics (MFCS 1) and Intro to Algorithms and Data Structures 1. OOP and UML modeling skills required. Java experience expected. SE1 or SE2 recommended. Algorithms & Data Structures Databases Software Engineering Network Technologies',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"51140\", \"__conflicts__\": {\"course_code\": [{\"course_code\": \"51140\", \"__conflicts__\": \"<circular-reference to root.courses[1].extras.__conflicts__>\"}, {\"course_code\": \"52715\"}]}}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(3,1,NULL,'COMPUTER SCIENCE 1 (LP)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"12.00\", \"6.00\"]','[]','[\"Bachelor\", \"Master\", \"Master / Bachelor Elective\", \"Master (Version 2022) / Bachelor Elective\"]','[]',NULL,'Students learn about threat scenarios in distributed systems by attacking network components and understanding memory corruption. The course focuses on practical binary exploitation and feasible network attacks.\n\nThe aim is to conduct an IT-oriented project in the field of Computer Science or Media Informatics. Based on the experience gained during the implementation, students learn to carry out IT projects independently. The course encourages the combination of previously acquired knowledge from various study areas.','Demonstrate a comprehensive understanding of complex project tasks. Enable the application of necessary concepts, techniques, and methods to achieve suitable solutions. Gain proficiency in independent project management and prototype development.',NULL,'Binary exploitation. Feasible network attacks. Chaining together different vulnerabilities in lab exercises. Threat scenarios in distributed communications.\n\n- Independent processing of project tasks (project-oriented approach). - Design and implementation of an IT prototype. - Written documentation and reporting. - Research groups offering topics include: MIS (Management of Information Systems), DM (Data Mining), SWA (Software Architecture), and SEC (Security).','Evaluation of the entire project, prototype implementation, and written report. Grading scale: 1 (≥87.5%), 2 (≥75.0%), 3 (≥62.5%), 4 (≥50.0%). Lab assignments (60%) and an exam (40%). Use of AI tools is strictly prohibited. Grading based on a formula.\n\nEvaluation of the entire project, the implementation of the prototype, and the final written report.',NULL,'A thorough knowledge of computer science is required; the thesis should be tackled in the final semester. Mandatory: None. Recommended: 18 ECTS in one of the relevant clusters.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"51080\", \"__conflicts__\": {\"course_code\": [{\"course_code\": \"51080\", \"__conflicts__\": \"<circular-reference to root.courses[2].extras.__conflicts__>\"}, {\"course_code\": \"53021\"}]}}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(4,1,NULL,'PARALLEL COMPUTING (VU)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"3.00\"]','[]','[\"Master\"]','[]',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Continuous assessment of coursework, including assignments, presentations, and participation.\n\nContinuous assessment of course work (assignments and participation).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"53039\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(5,1,NULL,'DISTRIBUTED AND PARALLEL ALGORITHMS (VU)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"6.00\"]','[]','[\"Master / Bachelor Elective\", \"Master Data Science / Master CS / Bachelor Elective\"]','[]',NULL,'Students will understand fundamental concepts of parallel computing, including parallelism, concurrency, and dependencies. The course bridges theory and practice through exercises for programming parallel processors and systems.','Students will understand fundamental concepts of parallel computing, including parallelism, concurrency, and performance analysis.\n\nIdentify dependencies and synchronization requirements. Apply parallelization strategies to computational problems. Perform performance analysis on parallel code.',NULL,'- Parallelism and concurrency. - Dependences, communication, and synchronization. - Major parallelization strategies. - Performance analysis of parallel programs. - Practical project work.\n\n- Parallelism and concurrency. - Communication, coordination, and synchronization. - Major parallelization strategies. - Basic methods for performance analysis of parallel programs. - Practical project work for parallel systems.','Based on partial assessments (assignments and tests). At least 30% must be reached on each, with an overall score of at least 50% and at most one negative assessment for a passing grade.\n\nBased on partial assessments (assignments and tests). Requirement for pass: At least 30% on each partial assessment and overall at least 50% with at most one negative partial assessment.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52800\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(6,1,NULL,'Parallelism as a Computing Primitive','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"6.00\"]','[]','[\"Elective\"]','[]',NULL,'The course provides an understanding of parallelism as a computing primitive and the challenges in distributed/parallel algorithms. It covers theoretical foundations and state-of-theart developments in algorithm design.','Recognize which paradigm is best suited for new problems.\nAnalyze correctness and time complexity of solutions.',NULL,'Distributed Graph Algorithms (Models: LOCAL, CONGEST, CONGESTED Clique).\nParallel Algorithms (Model: PRAM; problems: matrix multiplication, MST, shortest paths).','Exercises (20 pts), Quizzes (10 pts), Final Oral Exam (70 pts). At least 20 pts on the exam are needed to pass.',NULL,'Recommended: Discrete Mathematics and Introduction to Algorithms and Data Structures.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52114\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(7,1,NULL,'HIGH PERFORMANCE COMPUTING (VU)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"6.00\"]','[]','[]','[]',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Grading based on equally weighted assignments and an exam. A minimum of 50% must be earned in both.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52811\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(8,1,NULL,'PATTERNS AND ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE FOR CLOUD AND CLOUD-EDGE CONTINUUM (VU)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"6.00\"]','[]','[\"Master / Bachelor Elective\"]','[]',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Exercises (30%), Programming assignments (30%), Written midterm exam (20%), Written final exam (20%). A minimum of 50% on the combined exam scores is required.',NULL,'Recommended: Algorithms, Databases, Software Engineering, Network Technologies.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52813\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(9,1,NULL,'NETWORK SECURITY (VU)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"6.00\"]','[]','[\"Master / Bachelor Elective\"]','[]',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Programming tasks (30%), Presentations (20%), Written assignments (20%), Participation (10%), Written test (20%). - Minimum 50% required in each of the five parts to pass. Attendance is mandatory.',NULL,'Builds on the VU Cooperative Systems course.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52711\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(10,1,NULL,'NUMERICAL ALGORITHMS','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"3.00\"]','[]','[]','[]',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Written on-site exam: 79 points (Minimum 30 points required to pass). Online quizzes: 10 points. Mini-quizzes (Questions of the day): 11 points.','Discrete Mathematics (MFCS 1) and Algorithms and Data Structures 1.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52100\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(11,1,NULL,'SOFTWARE TOOLS FOR COMPUTATIONAL AND DATA SCIENCE (VU)','English',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"3.00\"]','[]','[\"Master / Bachelor\"]','[]',NULL,NULL,'Get acquainted with fundamental concepts of numerical algorithms including approximations, conditioning, and numerical stability. Understand the interplay between hardware, performance, accuracy, and data.',NULL,'Numerical computation approximations.\nTechniques for analysis (perturbation theory).\nImplementation and experimentation using Python.','2 Programming tests in Python (individual): 40 points total. 2 Written tests (closed-book, individual): 60 points total. Total required to pass: 50 points.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"52101\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:19:14',NULL),(12,2,NULL,'INTRODUCTION TO MATHEMATICAL MODELLING (VO)','German',NULL,NULL,'2026S','[\"3.00\"]','[]','[\"Bachelor\"]','[]',NULL,'The course aims to provide students with a foundational understanding of one- and multidimensional analysis. It focuses on the independent application of this knowledge to problems in economics, technology, and natural sciences. Students will also learn to use software tools for modeling and graphing, and develop skills in oral presentation.','Know the basics of one-dimensional and multidimensional analysis.\nApply this knowledge independently to solve simple problems.\nUse suitable software tools for modeling and graphing.\nCommunicate this knowledge in an oral presentation.',NULL,'One-dimensional analysis\nMultidimensional analysis\nApplication of analysis to simple problems in economics, technology, and natural sciences\nModeling and graphing using software tools\nSolving problems using the learned contents\nCommunication of knowledge in an oral presentation format','A 90-minute written examination on the lecture contents. Documents and electronic aids are not allowed. At least 50% of the maximum points must be achieved for a positive grade.',NULL,'Mastery of the content from \"MG1 - Mathematical Foundations of Computer Science 1\" and school-level mathematics (fractions, quadratic equations, etc.) is assumed.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'[]','{\"course_code\": \"51120\"}','[]','2026-05-19 18:28:12',NULL),(13,2